- wrap every testfile in at least one suite (why is there no eslint rule flagging this)
- now packtory has become quite sophisticated tool, with a bunch of hard to understand concepts/algorithms. I think we should provide some kind of "internal architecture" or "how-it-works-under-the-hood" documentation. The main readme.md already has a "concept" section but is very brief. I think we should have a dedicated document in documentation, that especially explains the stages/phases of packtory and what each stage does. And maybe some algos like how dependency scanning works, how DCE/tree-shaking works, how automatic version detection works etc. The language should have technial audience, but nevertheless it should be written in a very easy/understandable, especially the tree-shaking algo, which I dont even understand myself at the moment. Also feel free to utilize mermaid diagrams where it makes sense or latex annotations and Collapsible Sections or even STL when useful. We should maybe also talk about the scheduler and how it runs in parallel based on the graph generations etc. It should be very precise but at the same time very easy to understand for engineers who have e.g. never heard about tree-shaking and at the same time it should be very concise... so no unnecessary prose. Also how import path rewriting works should be explained. And whatever else you think is useful to document.
* new feature: reports... I am thinking of a file report (e.g. json or html I dont know yet) which gives you details that happened during the whole flow, e.g. what exaclty has been eliminated by DCE and why, what version  has be detected and why? etc etc. WDYT?
